            <biogHist>
                <p>Ranald or Ronald MacDonald was born to John MacDonald, sheep farmer, and Mary
                    MacDonald n√©e Maclennan in Taransay in the parish of Harris, Inverness-shire. In
                    1851 at the age of 17, he is found living with his elder sister Marjory, listed
                    as head of the household, and four other siblings: Donald, Roderica Catherine
                    and Donalda. It would appear that they were living next to their parents and
                    were all employed on their farm. By 1861, the family is listed together with
                    Ronald's father John recorded as head of the household, aged 81 and farmer of
                    700 acres. His elder brother Donald is listed as the farm manager. In 1871,
                    Ronald is still unmarried and living on the family farm with his siblings; his
                    mother, now widowed, is listed as head of the household. At the time of the 1881
                    census, Donald, Catherine and Donald are not longer listed as being at the farm
                    with only Ronald, Roderica and their mother recorded as head; at this time, the
                    farm employed 3 men and 2 women. In 1891, Ronald is listed as 'living on private
                    means' and as 'brother to Head' at Paible House, Taransay, presumably with
                    Donald now heading up the smaller household following is mother's death; his
                    sister Marjory is also listed as living on private means. By the 1901 census,
                    Ronald is listed as being age 60 and living in Taransay together with one
                    servant; a visiting wool spinner is also listed. </p>
                <p>He died of supposed old age in June 1913, having remained unmarried throughout
                    his life. There was no medical attendant present and the death certificate was
                    signed by his cousin Malcolm MacDonald. </p>
